apple: fruit with red or yellow or green skin and sweet to tart crisp whitish flesh
aquarium_fish: a tank or pool or bowl filled with water for keeping live fish and underwater animals
bear: massive plantigrade carnivorous or omnivorous mammals with long shaggy coats and strong claws
bee: any of numerous hairy-bodied insects including social and solitary species
bottle: a glass or plastic vessel used for storing drinks or other liquids; typically cylindrical without handles and with a narrow neck that can be plugged or capped
bowl: a round vessel that is open at the top; used chiefly for holding food or liquids
bridge: a structure that allows people or vehicles to cross an obstacle such as a river or canal or railway etc.
bus: a vehicle carrying many passengers; used for public transport
can: airtight sealed metal container for food or drink or paint etc.
castle: a large building formerly occupied by a ruler and fortified against attack
caterpillar: a wormlike and often brightly colored and hairy or spiny larva of a butterfly or moth
chair: a seat for one person, with a support for the back
clock: a timepiece that shows the time of day
cloud: a visible mass of water or ice particles suspended at a considerable altitude
cockroach: any of numerous chiefly nocturnal insects; some are domestic pests
couch: an upholstered seat for more than one person
cup: a small open container usually used for drinking; usually has a handle
dinosaur: any of numerous extinct terrestrial reptiles of the Mesozoic era
dolphin: any of various small toothed whales with a beaklike snout; larger than porpoises
forest: land that is covered with trees and shrubs
hamster: short-tailed Old World burrowing rodent with large cheek pouches
house: a dwelling that serves as living quarters for one or more families
kangaroo: any of several herbivorous leaping marsupials of Australia and New Guinea having large powerful hind legs and a long thick tail
keyboard: device consisting of a set of keys on a piano or organ or typewriter or typesetting machine or computer or the like
lawn_mower: garden tool for mowing grass on lawns
lion: large gregarious predatory feline of Africa and India having a tawny coat with a shaggy mane in the male
lizard: relatively long-bodied reptile with usually two pairs of legs and a tapering tail
lobster: any of several edible marine crustaceans of the families Homaridae and Nephropsidae and Palinuridae
mountain: a land mass that projects well above its surroundings; higher than a hill
mouse: any of numerous small rodents typically resembling diminutive rats having pointed snouts and small ears on elongated bodies with slender usually hairless tails
mushroom: fleshy body of any of numerous edible fungi
oak_tree: a deciduous tree of the genus Quercus; has acorns and lobed leaves
orange: round yellow to orange fruit of any of several citrus trees
orchid: any of numerous plants of the orchid family usually having flowers of unusual shapes and beautiful colors
palm_tree: any plant of the family Palmae having an unbranched trunk crowned by large pinnate or palmate leaves
pear: sweet juicy gritty-textured fruit available in many varieties
plate: dish on which food is served or from which food is eaten
porcupine: relatively large rodents with sharp erectile bristles mingled with the fur
possum: small furry Australian arboreal marsupials having long usually prehensile tails
rabbit: any of various burrowing animals of the family Leporidae having long ears and short tails; some domesticated and raised for pets or food
raccoon: an omnivorous nocturnal mammal native to North America and Central America
ray: cartilaginous fishes having horizontally flattened bodies and enlarged winglike pectoral fins with gills on the underside; most swim by moving the pectoral fins
road: an open way (generally public) for travel or transportation
seal: any of numerous marine mammals that come on shore to breed; chiefly of cold regions
shrew: small mouselike mammal with a long snout; related to moles
skunk: American musteline mammal typically ejecting an intensely malodorous fluid when startled; in some classifications put in a separate subfamily Mephitinae
skyscraper: a very tall building with many stories
snake: limbless scaly elongate reptile; some are venomous
spider: predatory arachnid with eight legs, two poison fangs, two feelers, and usually two silk-spinning organs at the back end of the body; they spin silk to make cocoons for eggs or traps for prey
squirrel: a kind of arboreal rodent having a long bushy tail
streetcar: a wheeled vehicle that runs on rails and is propelled by electricity
sunflower: any plant of the genus Helianthus having large flower heads with dark disk florets and showy yellow rays
tank: an enclosed armored military vehicle; has a cannon and moves on caterpillar treads
tiger: large feline of forests in most of Asia having a tawny coat with black stripes; endangered
train: public transport provided by a line of railway cars coupled together and drawn by a locomotive
trout: any of various game and food fishes of cool fresh waters mostly smaller than typical salmons
tulip: any of numerous perennial bulbous herbs having linear or broadly lanceolate leaves and usually a single showy flower
turtle: any of various aquatic and land reptiles having a bony shell and flipper-like limbs for swimming
willow_tree: any of numerous deciduous trees and shrubs of the genus Salix
wolf: any of various predatory carnivorous canine mammals of North America and Eurasia that usually hunt in packs
beaver: large semiaquatic rodent with webbed hind feet and a broad flat tail; construct complex dams and underwater lodges
beetle: insect having biting mouthparts and front wings modified to form horny covers overlying the membranous rear wings
butterfly: diurnal insect typically having a slender body with knobbed antennae and broad colorful wings
camel: cud-chewing mammal used as a draft or saddle animal in desert regions
cattle: domesticated bovine animals as a group regardless of sex or age
crab: decapod having eyes on short stalks and a broad flattened carapace with a small abdomen folded under the thorax and pincers
crocodile: large voracious aquatic reptile having a long snout with massive jaws and sharp teeth and a body covered with bony plates; of sluggish tropical waters
fox: alert carnivorous mammal with pointed muzzle and ears and a bushy tail; most are predators that do not hunt in packs
lamp: an artificial source of visible illumination
leopard: large feline of African and Asian forests usually having a tawny coat with black spots
man: an adult person who is male (as opposed to a woman)
maple_tree: any of numerous trees or shrubs of the genus Acer bearing winged seeds in pairs; north temperate zone
motorcycle: a motor vehicle with two wheels and a strong frame
plain: extensive tract of level open land
poppy: annual or biennial or perennial herbs having showy flowers
rose: any of many shrubs of the genus Rosa that bear roses
table: a piece of furniture having a smooth flat top that is usually supported by one or more vertical legs
tractor: a wheeled vehicle with large wheels; used in farming and other applications
woman: an adult female person (as opposed to a man)
baby: a very young child (birth to 1 year) who has not yet begun to walk or talk
bed: a piece of furniture that provides a place to sleep
bicycle: a wheeled vehicle that has two wheels and is moved by foot pedals
chimpanzee: intelligent somewhat arboreal ape of equatorial African forests
flatfish: sweet lean whitish flesh of any of numerous thin-bodied fish; usually served as thin fillets
otter: freshwater carnivorous mammal having webbed and clawed feet and dark brown fur
pickup_truck: a light truck with an open body and low sides and a tailboard
rocket: any vehicle self-propelled by a rocket engine
sea: a division of an ocean or a large body of salt water partially enclosed by land
shark: any of numerous elongate mostly marine carnivorous fishes with heterocercal caudal fins and tough skin covered with small toothlike scales
snail: freshwater or marine or terrestrial gastropod mollusk usually having an external enclosing spiral shell
sweet_pepper: plant bearing large mild thick-walled usually bell-shaped fruits; the principal salad peppers
telephone: electronic equipment that converts sound into electrical signals that can be transmitted over distances and then converts received signals back into sounds
television: an electronic device that receives television signals and displays them on a screen
wardrobe: a tall piece of furniture that provides storage space for clothes; has a door and rails or hooks for hanging clothes
whale: any of the larger cetacean mammals having a streamlined body and breathing through a blowhole on the head
worm: any of numerous relatively small elongated soft-bodied animals especially of the phyla Annelida and Chaetognatha and Nematoda and Nemertea and Platyhelminthes; also many insect larvae
organ: wind instrument whose sound is produced by means of pipes arranged in sets supplied with air from a bellows and controlled from a large complex musical keyboard
goose: web-footed long-necked typically gregarious migratory aquatic birds usually larger and less aquatic than ducks
file: office furniture consisting of a container for keeping papers in order
jellyfish: large siphonophore having a bladderlike float and stinging tentacles
missile: a rocket carrying a warhead of conventional or nuclear explosives; may be ballistic or directed by remote control
coral_reef: a reef consisting of coral consolidated into limestone
black-footed_ferret: musteline mammal of prairie regions of United States; nearly extinct
lipstick: makeup that is used to color the lips
rhinoceros_beetle: any of various large chiefly tropical beetles having horns on the head; pest on coconuts
stage: a large platform on which people can stand and can be seen by an audience
theater_curtain: a hanging cloth that conceals the stage from the view of the audience; rises or parts at the beginning and descends or closes between acts and at the end of a performance
Newfoundland: a breed of very large heavy dogs with a thick coarse usually black coat; highly intelligent dogs and vigorous swimmers; developed in Newfoundland
scoreboard: a large board for displaying the score of a contest (and some other information)
robin: small Old World songbird with a reddish breast
hotdog: a frankfurter served hot on a bun
upright: a piano with a vertical sounding board
unicycle: a vehicle with a single wheel that is driven by pedals
Saluki: old breed of tall swift keen-eyed hunting dogs resembling greyhounds; from Egypt and southwestern Asia
solar_dish: a concave mirror that concentrates the rays of the sun; can produce high temperatures
rock_beauty: gold and black butterflyfish found from West Indies to Brazil
ashcan: a bin that holds rubbish until it is collected
hourglass: a sandglass that runs for sixty minutes
white_wolf: wolf of Arctic North America having white fur and a black-tipped tail
horizontal_bar: gymnastic apparatus consisting of a bar supported in a horizontal position by uprights at both ends
three-toed_sloth: a sloth that has three long claws on each forefoot and each hindfoot
prayer_rug: a small rug used by Muslims during their devotions
toucan: brilliantly colored arboreal fruit-eating bird of tropical America having a very large thin-walled beak
combination_lock: lock that can be opened only by turning dials in a special sequence
garbage_truck: a truck for collecting domestic refuse
malamute: breed of sled dog developed in Alaska
mixing_bowl: bowl used with an electric mixer
house_finch: small finch originally of the western United States and Mexico
reel: winder consisting of a revolving spool with a handle; attached to a fishing rod
triceratops: huge ceratopsian dinosaur having three horns and the neck heavily armored with a very solid frill
consomme: clear soup usually of beef or veal or chicken
nematode: unsegmented worms with elongated rounded body pointed at both ends; mostly free-living but some are parasitic
carton: a box made of cardboard; opens by flaps on top
golden_retriever: an English breed having a long silky golden coat
poncho: a blanket-like cloak with a hole in the center for the head
king_crab: large edible crab of northern Pacific waters especially along the coasts of Alaska and Japan
meerkat: a mongoose-like viverrine of South Africa having a face like a lemur and only four toes
electric_guitar: a guitar whose sound is amplified by electrical means
wok: pan with a convex bottom; used for frying in Chinese cooking
dalmatian: a large breed having a smooth white coat with black or brown spots; originated in Dalmatia
tile_roof: a roof made of fired clay tiles
ladybug: small round bright-colored and spotted beetle that usually feeds on aphids and other insect pests
parallel_bars: gymnastic apparatus consisting of two parallel wooden rods supported on uprights
catamaran: a sailboat with two parallel hulls held together by single deck
green_mamba: green phase of the black mamba
dugong: sirenian tusked mammal found from eastern Africa to Australia; the flat tail is bilobate
tobacco_shop: a shop that sells pipes and pipe tobacco and cigars and cigarettes
Gordon_setter: a Scottish breed with a black-and-tan coat
street_sign: a sign visible from the street
barrel: a cylindrical container that holds liquids
fire_screen: a metal screen before an open fire for protection (especially against flying sparks)
yawl: a ship's small boat (usually rowed by 4 or 6 oars)
boxer: a breed of stocky medium-sized short-haired dog with a brindled coat and square-jawed muzzle developed in Germany
photocopier: a copier that uses photographic methods of making copies
cuirass: medieval body armor that covers the chest and back
slot: a slot machine that is used for gambling
harvestman: spiderlike arachnid with a small rounded body and very long thin legs
bookshop: a shop where books are sold
frying_pan: a pan used for frying foods
crate: a rugged box (usually made of wood); used for shipping
aircraft_carrier: a large warship that carries planes and has a long flat deck for takeoffs and landings
chime: a percussion instrument consisting of a set of tuned bells that are struck with a hammer; used as an orchestral instrument
Ibizan_hound: breed of slender agile medium-sized hound found chiefly in the Balearic Islands; said to have been bred originally by the Pharaohs of ancient Egypt
iPod: (trademark) a pocket-sized device used to play music files
holster: a sheath (usually leather) for carrying a handgun
worm_fence: rail fence consisting of a zigzag of interlocking rails
ear: the externally visible cartilaginous structure of the external ear
vase: an open jar of glass or porcelain used as an ornament or to hold flowers
spider_web: a web spun by spiders to trap insect prey
komondor: Hungarian breed of large powerful shaggy-coated white dog; used also as guard dog
bolete: any fungus of the family Boletaceae
trifle: a cold pudding made of layers of sponge cake spread with fruit or jelly; may be decorated with nuts, cream, or chocolate
African_hunting_dog: a powerful doglike mammal of southern and eastern Africa that hunts in large packs; now rare in settled area
cliff: a steep high face of rock
oboe: a slender double-reed instrument; a woodwind with a conical bore and a double-reed mouthpiece
carousel: a large, rotating machine with seats for children to ride or amusement
cannon: a large artillery gun that is usually on wheels
French_bulldog: small stocky version of the bulldog having a sleek coat and square head
school_bus: a bus used to transport children to or from school
Tibetan_mastiff: very large powerful rough-coated dog native to central Asia
snorkel: breathing device consisting of a bent tube fitting into a swimmer's mouth and extending above the surface; allows swimmer to breathe while face down in the water
ant: social insect living in organized colonies; characteristically the males and fertile queen have wings during breeding season; wingless sterile females are the workers
hair_slide: a decorative hinged clip that girls and women put in their hair to hold it in place
Arctic_fox: thickly-furred fox of Arctic regions; brownish in summer and white in winter
